```java
import java.util.Iterator;
import java.util.List;

public class Graph {
    // ...

    public UnmodifiableIterator<List<Object>> paddedPartition(Iterator<?> iterator, int size) {
        if (size <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Size must be positive");
        }

        List<Object> currentList = new ArrayList<>();
        List<Object>[] result = new List[size];

        try {
            Iterator<?> iter = iterator;
            while (iter.hasNext()) {
                Object element = iter.next();
                if (currentList.size() == size) {
                    result[currentList.size() - 1] = currentList;
                    currentList = new ArrayList<>();
                }
                currentList.add(element);
            }

            if (!currentList.isEmpty()) {
                currentList = currentList.subList(0, size - 1);
            }
        } catch (NoSuchElementException e) {
            // Handle exception
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < result.length; i++) {
            if (i == result.length - 1 && !currentList.isEmpty()) {
                result[i] = currentList;
            } else {
                result[i] = new ArrayList<>(currentList);
            }
        }

        return UnmodifiableIterator.of(result);
    }
}
```

Note that the `UnmodifiableIterator` class and the `ArrayList` class are used to create an unmodifiable iterator of lists. The `paddedPartition` method takes an `Iterator<?>` as input, partitions it into sublists of the specified size, and returns an unmodifiable iterator over these sublists. If there are remaining elements after filling the last sublist, they are padded with null values.
